data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType`, which gives a clear failure message instead of throwing an `InvalidCastException` on wrong types:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

**Why this is better:**
- A wrong type produces a descriptive test failure instead of an unhandled `InvalidCastException`
- `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>` (MSTest v2.2+) is the generic form — cleaner than the older `Assert.IsInstanceOfType(result, typeof(EmailHandler))`

If you only need the type check and don't need to inspect properties, you can drop the cast and `AreEqual` entirely.
